<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Print on Demand</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<h5><a href="index.htm">P svenska tack!</a></h5>

<p><font size="6"><strong>BOOKS ON DEMAND!<br>
SWEDISH WRITERS PUBLISH THEIR OWN BOOKS ON THE INTERNET</strong></font></p>

<p><font size="4">PRESS CONFERENCE<br>
3 p.m. January 20 at Arkitektkopia,<br>
Drottninggatan 75, Stockholm</font></p>

<p><font size="3">If you're unable to attend, there's more
information to be had at Web address </font><a
href="http://www.marebalticum.se"><font size="3">http://www.marebalticum.se</font></a></p>

<p><font size="3">We as writers now take an initiative that
publishers, in our view, should long ago have taken. We point to,
and make use of, a new technology: Print-On-Demand. We also make
use of new opportunities of ordering books via the Internet. All
this put together enable us now to publish the first books in
1997 in this novel fashion.</font></p>

<p><a href="../curman/index-eng.htm"><font size="3"><strong>Peter
Curman</strong></font></a><font size="3"> publishes a hitherto
unpublished collection of satirical poems, which caused
considerable commotion when it was first presented on Swedish
television. Peter Curman also republishes a number of his poetry
books, today out of print, plus a collection of his own poetry in
Turkish.</font></p>

<p><a href="../forssell"><font size="3"><strong>Lars Forssell</strong></font></a><font
size="3"> publishes a new book of poems entitled
&quot;Rimfrost&quot; (&quot;Rime&quot;).</font></p>

<p><a href="../myrdal"><font size="3"><strong>Jan Myrdal</strong></font></a><font
size="3"> publishes two new volumes on literature. A collection
of essays in English: &quot;August Strindberg and Ole Edvart Roelvaag,
or The Literary Importance of Being Nordic&quot;, as well as a
collection in Swedish: &quot;I de svarta fanornas tid. Texter om
litteratur, lgn och frbannad dikt&quot;.</font></p>

<p><a href="bokbestallning970114.htm">Order form</a> - from
monday 20th you can order your own copy this way!</p>

<p><font size="3">Journalists will receive review copies at the
press conference.</font></p>

<h3><font size="4">Why do we take this step?</font></h3>

<p><font size="3">Because chaos reigns in the Swedish book
market. The situation is in fact even worse than chaotic. It
amounts to no less than a crisis for the book itself. The county
town of Lule has a county governor - but no book store! A quite
unheard of phenomenon in all of Europe.</font></p>

<p><font size="3">Publishers tread water. They have terminated
agreements with both writers and booksellers; they've even
changed their name, in Swedish, from the Swedish Book Publishers
Association to the Swedish Publishers Association as an
adjustment to new technology - but have made no progress at all. </font></p>

<p><font size="3">We now demonstrate, in co-operation with </font><a
href="http://www.akopia.se" target="_blank"><font size="3">Arkitektkopia</font></a><font
size="3">, how one with the aid of Internet and modern printing
equipment in less than two minutes can transform binary digits in
a data base into complete books; two or two hundred copies
depending on how many you need at exactly that moment, and at a
very favourable price. The Japanese call this &quot;lean
production&quot;. </font></p>

<p><font size="3">This does not imply that we're starting up a
new publishing house; it is advatageous for us to be able to make
use of properly staffed publishing houses managing design,
marketing, distribution and so forth. Our aim is to just point
publishers to what can be achieved. They've got to take this to
heart and reach the new agreements that new technology calls for.
The alternative is that present day publishers become as obsolete
as lamplighters in their day. </font></p>

<p><font size="3">In order to cope with the present crises in the
book market, the Minister of Culture has appointed Ms. Anna-Greta
Leijon to suggest proper methods in order to strengthen the
overall position of the book. This is admirable. We wish the
minister every success, in her endeavours while we're at the same
time anxious to demonstrate to her the fresh possibilities that
this new technology opens up. </font></p>

<p><font size="3">The Swedish Institute can no longer supply
students with course literature - the books simply aren't
available! All of Swedish literature can now be made available. A
teacher of Swedish Literature in the US, China or Germany who
wishes to order 15 copies of Ellen Key or 15 copies of Olaus
Petri can now do so by placing an order via an Internet address.</font></p>

<p><font size="3">The press conference will also be attended by
international representatives from the new </font><a
href="../seminar/index.htm"><font size="3">Writers' and
Translators' Centre of Rhodes</font></a><font size="3">. They can
supply information on how this new technology revolutionizes the
possibilities to supply Swedish readers with new literature from
the Black Sea area, from Greece, or for that matter India or
Argentina.</font></p>

<p><font size="3">We do not regard publishers as our enemies, we
extend our hand to them. If they fulfill their obligations to
bring our books to market, we, on our hand, will fulfil our
obligations to write them! </font></p>

<table border="0" width="70%">
    <tr>
        <td><em>Peter Curman</em></td>
        <td><em>Lars Forssell</em></td>
        <td><em>Jan Myrdal</em></td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr>

