<html>

<head>
<title>Islamabad</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFF80">
<p><a href="islamabad.htm"><strong>Article</strong></a><strong> on the meeting (in Swedish)</strong></p>
<hr>
<h1>Islamabad Declaration</h1>
<p>Writers, artists and intellectuals from around 100 countries of the world, having met in 
Islamabad from Nov 30 to Dec 03, 1995. </p>
<p>-- Realizing the commitment that writers, artists, cultural workers and intellectuals have to the 
promotion of democracy, peace, freedom of expression and the culture of love and tolerance. </p>
<p>-- Recalling the efforts that writers and artists have made in all lands to the realization of all 
peoples' right to peace and justice, often at grave risks to their lives and well-being. </p>
<p>-- Recognizing the rights of all peoples, regardless of the level of their political, social and 
economic development, to pursue the ideals of participatory democracy, truth, and cultural 
refinement, to develop their languages, cultures and literatures in freedom, and to profit from 
each other's experience and accomplishment. </p>
<p>-- Noting that over large parts of the world men and women are still suffering denial of their 
basis rights and opportunities to realize themselves, and that several communities are being 
subjected to denial of human rights and hardships because of lack of equal respect for the 
fundamental rights of all peoples. </p>
<p>-- Reaffirming the duty of all, writers, artists and intellectuals to continue their struggle, severally 
and collectively. for national and international orders based on respect for the dignity of all 
human beings. </p>
<p>-- Appreciating the consensus emerging from the presentations made at the conference and the 
wide-ranging exchange of ideas among the distinguished delegates on the ideals and aspirations 
of the international community of the writers, artists and intellectuals, viz, peace, democracy, rule 
of law, human rights, especially the individuals and people's right to freedom of expression and 
freedom from fear, want and hunger and protection against all forms of hegemony, foreign 
occupation, oppression and exploitation, adopts the following declaration:</p>
<p><strong>1.</strong><br>
The world has undergone tremendous political, ideological and technological upheavals in the 
past - same beneficial while others injurious to humanity as a whole. Conferences such as this 
are the need of the hour to bring round the writers and intellectuals to synthesize all that is good, 
noble and humane for the destiny of humankind. </p>
<p><strong>2.</strong><br>
All writers, artists, and intellectuals must redouble their efforts to foster and consolidate peace 
and amity in their own societies and among the nations of the world, especially by conducting a 
sustained and concerted struggle to banish war and all form of violence and violation of human 
rights, particularly of children, women, minorities, and the economically under-privileged. </p>
<p><strong>3.</strong><br>
It is absolutely essential that writers, artists and intellectuals in all countries of the world should 
be free to travel across national frontiers and all barriers to the flow of information, exchange of 
literature, and inter-mingling of cultures must be demolished. </p>
<p><strong>4.</strong><br>
To realize their ideals the writers, artists and intellectuals resolve to discourage all forms of 
political, social, economic and cultulral hegemony, to persuade all states and communities to 
settle disputes and differcllces among them througll dialogue instcad of annex confiicts and 
confrolltatioll, and to pool their resources to eliminate the kolossal waSte of global resources so 
that the ideals of distributive justice can be realized by the entire humankind. The conference 
further calls upon all states to substantially reduce their defence expenditures and devote larger 
resources to education and culture. </p>
<p><strong>5.</strong><br>
Although organizations such as UNESCO have a mandate to achieve the aims and objectives 
mentioned above, and many organizations of writers, artists and intellectuals at different levels 
are also pursuing these goals, there is room for more worldwide forum to promote the unity of 
the human familj out of the diversity of ideologies, concerns and inte rests, and ensure a happy 
future for the coming generations. </p>
<p><strong>6.</strong><br>
The delegates gratefully accept the offer mede by Pakistan to host such an organisation under 
the title of international Congress of Writers, Artists and lntellectuals (lCWAI), and proclaim the 
present conference as the first convention of the International Congress of Writers and 
Intellectuals. </p>
<p><strong>7.</strong><br>
The conference authorizes the Chairman, Pakistan Academy of Letters, to draft the charter and 
constitution of the proposed ICWAI in consultation with the heads of delegations. </p>
<p><strong>8.</strong><br>
The participants of the conference record their appreciation of the initiative taken by the 
Pakistan Academy of Letters in bringing them together, acknowledge the contribution made to 
the conference by the President and the Prime Minister of Pakistan, and sincerely thank the 
organizers for making their delibretions positive and fruitful and their stay in Islamabad happy 
and enjoyable. </p>
<h2>Recommendation</h2>
<p>The Drafting Committee recommends to all those who will be responsible for preparator work 
for ICWAI that persian should be one of the official languages of ICWAI. </p>
<p>The committee also recommends that the conference adopts a resolution condemning the 
persecution of writers, artists and intellectuals any where in the world, their incarceration 
censorship and supression of publications and curbs on art. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.marebalticum.se/index.htm" target="_top"><strong>Home of Marebalticum</strong></a></p>
</body>

</html>
