<head>
<title>Baltic Centre for Writers and Translators - National Reports</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/bakgr.gif" link="#800019" vlink="#4B4D4C">
<div align=center><center>
<table COLSPEC="L20 L20">
<tr><td><img src="../images/OVCENTRU.GIF" align=bottom width=180 height=137></td><td><font size=6>B</font><font size=5>ALTIC </font><font size=6>C</font><font size=5>ENTRE FOR<br>
</font><font size=6>W</font><font size=5>RITERS AND </font><font size=6>T</font><font size=5>RANSLATORS</font></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>National Reports</h1>
<p><a name="denmark"><font size=4><strong>The Danish</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> Writers Association</strong></font></p>
<p>The Danish Writers Association has 1.350 members, divided into five professional groups, 
each of which seek to promote its specific interests. The groups consist of the Fiction 
Group, The Poetry Group, the Group of Writers of Books for Children and Young people, 
the Non-Fiction Group and the Danish Translators Union.</p>
<p>At our general meeting, November 11th, 1995, the chairman Mette Koefoed Bjornsen was 
reelected. Just now the association is electing the members of the executive committee, 
which consists of 10 members, five of those elected by ballot among the members, five by 
the boards of the professional groups. The new executive committee is going to start its 2 
years period in January 1996.</p>
<p>In 1995 the Folketing (The Danish Parliament) passed a new law on copyright. We had 
hoped that the law would take into consideration &quot;electronic age&quot; stressing the rights of 
authors in this connection. The government, however, declared that it was too early to do 
so. We therefore have to fight for our rights ourselves, and so we try to do, e.g. by meetings 
with the other associations of authors. We would like to start a Danish ALIS, but till now 
the discussion between the authors stay discussions. There is a great sympathy for the ALIS 
idea but not a common conviction of the necessity of such an organisation.</p>
<p>In the years to come we expect a revision of the Library Lending Act. A special committee 
of our association is trying to agree on the necessary improvements of the law in order to be 
able to introduce the minister and the Folketing to some needed emendations of the law.</p>
<p>We are also working hard to convince the politicians of the need for a legislation on the 
social security of the authors who in some periods are not able to live by their income as 
artists, and for the amendment of the fiscal legislation in favour of the special 
working-conditions of authors. In collaboration with our Swedish colleagues we in 
September started a Danish- Swedish Writers Society. We want to strengthen our links to 
the neighbouring writers and to deepen the artistic and intellectual Danish - Swedish 
&quot;brother- and sisterhood&quot;.</p>
<p>And just now we are looking forward to two events: a legislation on literature promised by 
the minister of culture, and Copenhagen European capital 1996.</p>
<p>Happy New Year to all members of the Baltic Writers Council.</p>
<p>Thank you for good meetings in 1995. You are always welcome in the Danish Writers 
Association.</p>
<p>Ingerlise Koefoed</p>
<p><a name="estonia"><font size=4><strong>Estonian</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> Writers Union</strong></font></p>
<p>The situation of Estonian writers and their organisation is the same as in the society they are 
living in slowly stabilising by adapting and following the new rules of the game - market 
economy. The Estonian state and it&#180;s foundation The Culture Capital are awakening to the 
understanding that culture, especially of a small nation, is not able to compete according to 
the strict rules of the system. It must be supported by representative bodies of the national 
state, and that&#180;s the way we are approaching this crucial question. But it takes time.</p>
<p>We are preparing ourselves for important negotiations with our Government about systems 
existing elsewhere in the world, like the Public Lending Right, etc. We are trying to establish 
a functioning collecting society, dedicated to the special concerns of the writers guild. We 
are trying to find a proper form for the promotion of our literature home and abroad by 
establishing a special Centre and arranging seminars for our known and new translators into 
other languages. We are calculating how much it would cost to start a kind of Literature 
House in Estonia with facilities for writers to work and repose...</p>
<p>We are hoping for the success of the PHARE-project about networking the Baltic literary 
region.</p>
<p>We believe that things could have been worse, we hope that they are turning better, we love 
what we are doing.</p>
<p>Matti Sirkel<br>
Chairman,<br>
Estonian Writers Union<br>
Tallinn, 1995.30.11.</p>
<p><a name="finland"><font size=4><strong>News from Finland</strong></font></a></p>
<p>Hannu Makela&#180;s Mestari (The Master), a biographical novel about Eino Leino, Finland&#180;s 
most powerful &quot;neo-romantic&quot; poet, has won the 1995 Finlandia Prize. The award, which is 
worth FIM 100 000, is Finland&#180;s biggest literary prize. Hannu Makela (1943) is a prolific 
author, who has written 57 books, including novels, short stories, and collections of poems. 
He has also edited several influential anthologies and written many plays. He is well-known 
too for his popular children&#180;s stories about Herra Huu (&quot;Mr Boo&quot;).</p>
<p>This years shortlist for Runebers award, the literary prize founded by The University of 
Finnish Writers, the Newspaper Uusima and The Finnish Critics Association, was 
announced in November. The prize is awarded to a new work of prose fiction or poetry. 
The shortlist was as follows: Helena Anhava&#180;s Eihan Elamale mitaan voi (You can&#180;t do 
anything about life, short stories), Agneta Ara&#180;s Huset med gl&ouml;mda d&ouml;rrar (The house with 
forgotten doors, novel), Tomas Mikael B&auml;cks Tr&auml;dg&aring;rdssten (Garden Stones, poems), Eila 
Kivikk&#180;aho&#180;s Ruusukvartsi (Rosequartz, poems), Tomi Kontio&#180;s Uumen (The Depths, 
novel), Leena Krohn&#180;s Ettei et&auml;isyys ik&auml;v&ouml;isi (That the distance would not yearn, short 
stories), Jusa Peltoniemi&#180;s Pieni el&auml;mantanssi (A small dance of living, poems) and Nalle 
Valtiala&#180;s Tang (Tang, novel). The final winner will be announced in February 1996.</p>
<p>Anna Baijars<br>
The Union of Finnish Writers</p>
<p><strong>The Finnish Association of Translators and Interpreters</strong> has got a new president, 
Kristiina Rikman. She translates modern English and American fiction into Finnish and is 
known above all as the translator of John Irving&#180;s books. Kristiina Rikman was the 
chairperson of our literary translator&#180;s section since 1993 and will now be succeeded by 
Anna-Maija Viltanen, a translator of French literature. Among Anna-Maija&#180;s latest 
translations let us mention Flaubert&#180;s Madame Bovary and several works by Simone de 
Beauvoir.</p>
<p>The previous president of the whole Association, Heikki Kaskimies, translator of English 
and American fiction, presided over our Association for 13 years altogether (1978-1986 
and 1992-1995). Heikki will continue as a member of the Board of Association.</p>
<p>Kristiina Drews,<br>
vice-president<br>
The Finnish Association of Translators and Interpreters</p>
<p><a name="germany"><font size=4><strong>The situation</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> of Literature in Germany in the 6th year after 
Unification</strong></font></p>
<p>Judging from the last Frankfurt Book fair, literature is making gigantic progress: more than 
350.000 new titles, electronic publishing in every hall, Austria spending some 50 million DM 
on their being the centre point of interest, with one pavilion plus two weeks literary events in 
the Frankfurt Literature House as well as Austrian plays at the theatre and Austrian music at 
the opera.</p>
<p>However, apart form that, throughout the country there is shortage of cultural money, 
especially in the field of literature. Libraries in the former GDR are still closing down. 
Publishers and small booksellers go bankrupt because of high rents and impossible transport 
and storage costs. The big Media Union, of which we are but a small part, cannot afford 
any longer to send two delegates to any international conference, but have to reduce 
themselves to one. Some scholarships threaten to finish. For example, there is one grant that 
allows a writer (or painter or composer) to stay for nine months, with a monthly pay of 
1.500 DM, in a specially equipped historical artists house in Lower Saxony. The 1996 
winners of the scholarship had to wait one and a half year to be told because there wasn&#180;t 
any only to pay them. Only after very outspoken protests of cultural people in radio and 
newspaper interviews did the government refrain from letting the whole project die away, 
without anybody noticing.</p>
<p>On the other hand, there is hope. Some new developments are very encouraging. In Leipzig, 
there will be a new literature house inaugurated in 1996. The Leipzig Bookfair may be 
regarded as safe now, being especially dedicated to contacts to Eastern countries. In 
Hamburg, the first European Writers Room has opened place, where writers can find all 
modern equipment ranging from computers to scanners, from laser prints to fax machine. 
There is a small kitchen to make tee or coffee, and an office where each member has her/his 
own mail box. The costs to rent a working place are low: 50 DM for half a day, 100 DM 
for a full day per month. Undisturbed by any private inconveniences and everyday trouble, 
writers may work there, having access to archives and nearly all important libraries of the 
world by apt data highway instalments. In addition, the Hamburg Writers Room offers 
seminars to beginners as well as advanced writers in various fields such as radio drama or 
crime novels. These courses are held by qualified members of according interest. 
Discussions with foreign writers that visits the city and working facilities offers to refugee 
writers from Bosnia are also integral part of its program. The Writers Room is subsidised by 
the State and City of Hamburg and so far regarded to be a great success. At the 
inauguration the officials pointed out that despite the present shortage of public money, it 
was created in close cooperation with writers organisations, and with the help of sponsors.</p>
<p>Uwe Friesel</p>
<p><a name="iceland"><font size=4><strong>A short report</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> from the Writers Union of Iceland to the Annual 
meeting of the Baltic Council in Visby</strong></font></p>
<p>In the Baltic Newsletter 2:1994 there was a short description of the Writers Union of 
Iceland. There we told you that one of our tasks at the moment was trying to get the 
authorities to change the law concerning the remuneration to authors for books in libraries. 
We are still negotiating about this - its seems to be a very slow process, but we still hope 
that in the end we will see some results, hopefully next year.</p>
<p>We are also negotiating with the Icelandic State Radio and TV about the renewal and 
revision of our contract with that institution - another slow process where we hope to see 
some result soon.</p>
<p>It seems that the authorities agree with us about the necessity of a Literature Information 
centre. A committee which consisted of representatives of the Writers Union, the Publishers 
Union and the Fund for the Promotion of Icelandic Literature Abroad together with one 
person from the Ministry of Education and Culture has now delivered a paper with 
suggestions for the founding of such a centre. This proposal is being discussed by the 
various interested organisations, and after that it is hoped that our minister of Education and 
Culture will push it through the parliament.</p>
<p>Last month we handed out for the first time 12 stipends of 100.00 Icelandic crowns 
(approx. 10.000 Swedish crowns) from the money that comes on from the tax laid on 
video-recorders and empty videotapes and audiocassettes. At our annual meeting in April 
we voted in the new rules for the handing out of this money, and according to the rules we 
put an announcement in the media, asking for applications for the stipends. People have to 
prove that they are authors of works that have been on TV or radio. 45 people applied for 
the 12 stipends, and a special committee had the difficult task of choosing the lucky ones. 
These stipends will from now on be handed out once a year, as long as we get this money. 
It is a pleasant addition to the other stipends people can apply for.</p>
<p>We have been told that the Institute of Free Trade and Competition that our contract with 
the publishers does not agree with the new laws in this field and something has to be done 
about that. Our lawyer is at present working on this problem and probably will soon be 
hearing from our publishers something about this. We have asked for information from the 
other Nordic countries and got very good response, fro which we are thankful. This is a 
problem that will most likely be taking up a lot of our time soon.</p>
<p>There are other problems too, the situation here in the publishing branch is quite scarring - it 
seems that very soon we will have maybe two big (by Icelandic standards) publishing 
houses that will control the market - the other firms are having financial problems and 
several have even gone bankrupt already. This is a process we believe is going on elsewhere 
too, the concentration of capital and power in very few hands.</p>
<p>In April we organised a Writers Forum on the subject Author Rights in the Light of the New 
technology. It was quite a success, many people attended, and seven knowledgeable 
persons lectured about the different aspects of this very important theme. We have not 
found any solutions to the problems that come with the new technology, but we try to keep 
ourselves informed about what happens in other countries and apply good ideas to our 
situation when possible.</p>
<p>In September there was an International Literature Festival in Reykjavik, the fourth of its 
kind since 1985. Around 30 writers came from abroad, mostly from the Nordic countries 
but also from other parts of the world, The Writers Union as such was not a direct 
participant in the Festival, but we invited the foreign guests to a reception in our office to 
meet Icelandic colleagues, and of course members participated actively in the events of the 
festival. As you can imagine, many other things happened in this last year, but I think I have 
told you about the most important ones. I wish you all a very successful meeting in Visby.</p>
<p>Reykjavik, 18.10. 1995</p>
<p>Ingibj&ouml;rg Haraldsdottir<br>
president of the Writers Union of Iceland</p>
<p><a name="latvia"><font size=4><strong>Latvian</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> Writers Union</strong></font></p>
<p>The year has passed without really serious crisis, but also without any tangible progress or 
real success. The new government has not been formed yet, so we still lack a real partner in 
dialogue about may issues of importance.</p>
<p>Latvian Writers Union was very glad to host the International Seminar for Translators and 
Publishers of Latvian literature. It took place in Riga on December 8-10 and was sponsored 
by Soros Foundation-Latvia and Latvian Ministry of Culture. The guests - both translators 
and persons concerned with or interested in Latvian literature in many other ways listened to 
reports on Latvian poetry, prose, drama, juvenile literature, information on publishers 
dealing with original Latvian fiction and cultural magazines and newspapers. Among the 
guests were Ingrida and Ivars Alksni from Switzerland, Juris Kronbergs, Gunilla Fors&eacute;n and 
Annette Glover from Stockholm, Mara Kalnins and Hugh Macpherson from U.K., Peter 
Manfred Hein and Bernhardt Horst, German translators from Finland, Margita Gutmane 
from Germany, Sergij Paniznink from Bielorussia, Lembit Vaba from Estonia, Silvestr 
Gaizunas from Lithuania, Jatta Krug, Helen Johansson and Elisabeth Nordgren from 
Finland, Jerzi Litvinuk and Axel Holvoet from Poland, Larisa Bespalova, Irina Doronina, 
Vladimir Kornilov, Natalia Vorobyova and Vladimir Britansski from Russia. The guests had 
also many occasions to mix in more informal atmosphere with Latvian writers, and we have 
the impression that these meetings will prove to have been extremely fruitful.</p>
<p>Poet Uldis Berzins has been awarded the Baltic prize in literature, which last year went to 
Estonian writer Emil Tode.</p>
<p>Inguna Bekere<br>
International Secretary<br>
Latvian Writers Union</p>
<p><font size=4><strong>The Main Events in the Lithuanian Writers Union from October 
1994 to October 1995</strong></font></p>
<p>December 1994. The Copyright Law was adopted and the Bern Convention was signed.</p>
<p>December 1994. The Congress of the Lithuanian Writers Union (LRS) was held. A literary 
critic, Valentinas Sventickas, was elected as the Chairman. The new Regulations were 
adopted.</p>
<p>March 1995. The Lithuanian Association of Artists Unions was founded. The project of the 
Associations Statute was proposed to Seimas (Parliament) consideration.</p>
<p>March 1995. The Cooperation Agreement with the Union of Finnish Writers was signed. It 
is the eighth agreement with a foreign writers union.</p>
<p>May 1995. The annual international poetry festival POEZIJOS PAVASARIS (POETRY 
SPRING) took place in Vilnius, Kaunas and other places in Lithuania. Along with the 
Lithuanian writers guests from Australia, Austria, Denmark, Finland, Germany, Latvia, the 
Ukraine, the USA participated in it. The significant event of the Festival was the international 
discussion of the relationship of artists and society.</p>
<p>In 1994-1995 two issues of the Writers union magazine VILNIUS appeared in English. It is 
the only English publication of the kind in Lithuania.</p>
<p>June 1995. A seminar dedicated to the120th anniversary of Thomas Mann, organised by 
Goethe Institut in Riga was held in Nadir. LRS shared the organisational works of the 
Seminar and made its contribution to the presentation given there.</p>
<p>The Government allocated 3,7 million Lt (925 000) for the State Books Publishing Program 
and cultural press. However, it should be noticed that despite the Government promises to 
help culture and the State fellowships for artists, the living conditions of artists and writers 
still remain hardly bearable and are even getting worse.</p>
<p>Valentinas Sventickas<br>
Chairman</p>
<p><a name="norway"><font size=4><strong>News from</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> the Norwegian Association of Literary Translators</strong></font></p>
<p>Since last time, our association has arranged the traditional &quot;Autumn seminar&quot; for our 
members, a seminar that takes place over three days in a hotel situated on a little island 
south of Oslo. Every year has a special theme; this year we discussed the &quot;mutations&quot; of the 
world languages, regional use of English, French, etc. and the translations of such texts. Our 
key note speaker was Susan Basnett form the University of Warwick, who held a very 
interesting speech with the title, &quot;Translation, Sex and Politics&quot;. To these seminars we always 
invite a foreign colleague, and this year Ljuba Gorlina from Moscow, an eminent translator 
of Scandinavian literature, told us about the situation for literary translations in Russia.</p>
<p>Another traditional arrangement is our &quot;Christmas Meeting&quot;, where we discuss professional 
and literary issues. This year we had invited a computer specialist who talked about &quot;The 
translators&#180; electronic future&quot;, with a following discussion on the consequences of the 
development of electronic media (such as the world-wide electronic highways) for literary 
translators.</p>
<p>The Association has, as always, an extended international dialogue. We have decided to 
join the Baltic electronic network, and look forward to communicate with our fellow 
organisations on e-mail. The planning of the translators seminar in Visby in may next year is 
continuing; we have sent an application for the necessary money to the Nordic Cultural 
Fund and to Kopinor (the Norwegian collecting society). As soon as we get an answer, 
hopefully positive, we will send invitations to the participant translators organisations.</p>
<p>Bente Christensen, chairperson,<br>
Norwegian Association of Literary Translators</p>
<p><a name="poland"><font size=4><strong>News from</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> the Association of Polish Writers</strong></font></p>
<p>This information comes on behalf of the Association of Polish Writers and also partly of the 
Polish PEN club because we often face similar problems, both in political as literary aspects, 
have similar goals and achievements and many members of our Association belong also to 
the PEN Club.</p>
<p>Our problems and wishes were expressed in the report (which is rather a postulate) for the 
Tallinn conference of ministers of culture. Here are some fragments of it for those who might 
be interests.</p>
<p>In some points brought up in this report, a few positive aspects can lately be noticed:<br>
- the &quot;high culture&quot;, though very poorly supported, shows up more and more frequently on 
the market. Many good books are published which can counterbalance the &quot;low culture&quot; of 
the bestsellers, very aggressive after we regained freedom.<br>
- the regional cultures do quite well, often much better than our metropolitan centre, mostly 
because they are sponsored by local authorities. We have remarkable writers and poets 
living and working in smaller towns, where interesting projects are born and carried out. For 
example, their libraries for children and young people organise literary competitions for 
school-children, very much attended and successful. Also in provincial towns the new 
private publishing houses do well and show a lot of initiative.</p>
<p>Our Association notices with pleasure the activity and efficiency of our 10 branches in the 
regional centres, as well in big, as in smaller localities. Unfortunately there seems to reign 
some sort of paralysing atmosphere in our capital city.</p>
<p>Nevertheless we can mention a scientific session, organised by the PEN Club, celebrating 
the 5th anniversary of the abolition of the censorship and also our protest again recent 
attempts of the ruling post-communist party to restrain the freedom of expression, as it 
happened, for example, in one of our towns where the Supreme Court questioned in its 
sentence the rights of journalists not to reveal the names of their collocutors (after many 
protests this case was to be verified again by the Court). Our Association has lively contacts 
with the associations of writers in Germany, which are very active and have many initiatives. 
In September, we had a common friendship-cruise on the river Odra with readings and 
lectures.</p>
<p>We also develop contacts with the Union of Writers of Ukraine, some of our members have 
visited them several times, and these contacts would certainly develop much better if not for 
the permanent lack of money on both sides.</p>
<p>The Polish PEN Club in collaboration with Amnesty International works for the liberation of 
the Vietnamese (but not only) prisoners of conscience this year, because of the anniversary 
of Tienanmen, was collecting on the streets of Warsaw signatures under a petition for the 
release of Chinese prisoners of conscience.</p>
<p>This spring we celebrated the 50th anniversary of the weekly &quot;Tygodnik Powszechy&quot;, edited 
in Krakow, the very significant periodical which during the 45 years of communist regime in 
Poland was always, though of course in a veiled way, representing the ideas of the Polish 
opposition.</p>
<p>As usual quite a number of authors and translators got significant prizes and awards - 
national as well as foreign but we will quote their names in the next Newsletter.</p>
<p>What should certainly be mentioned now is the prize of the Polish PEN Club granted to 
Anders Bodeg&aring;rd for his translations of Polish prose and poetry into Swedish. This 
ceremony was a very &quot;warm&quot; one, the big audience applauded with enthusiasm and Anders 
delivered a speech, which was in fact a very interesting essay, in excellent Polish! We 
appreciated it and admired him very much.</p>
<p>Teresa Chlapowska<br>
International Secretary<br>
The Association of Polish Writers<br>
Warsaw, October 20, 1995</p>
<p><a name="st petersburg"><font size=4><strong>Writers Union</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> of St. Petersburg</strong></font></p>
<p>Writers Union of St. Petersburg became full member of the European Writers Congress at 
its XIX meeting in May.</p>
<p>St. Petersburg writers took part in the concert on May 9th, to celebrate the 50th 
Anniversary of the World war II Victory.</p>
<p>Three St. Petersburg writers have been awarded in June the newly established &quot;Northern 
Palmira&quot; Literary prize (Russia) - Alexander Koushner (poetry), Felix Roziner (prose), Felix 
Lourieur (critics.)</p>
<p>On September 1st-3rd the Writers Union of St. Petersburg organised a conference of 
young writers in Writers Creative House in Komarovo village. The members of our Writers 
Union delivered lectures for more than 25 participants writing in different genres. Two of 
them were recommended to join the Writers Union, three of them - for participation in 
All-Russian conference of young writers in Yaroslavl /January/.</p>
<p>St. Petersburg PEN Club members held a conference on September 14-16th together with 
their colleagues from Estonia and Finland in Writers Creative House in Komarovo (the 
subject was: &quot;Power and Culture&quot;). St. Petersburg writers D.Granin, V.Krivoulin, V.Popov, 
E.Putilova, I.Shtemler and the Mayor of St. Petersburg A. Sobchak took part in this work.</p>
<p>Poetry section led by Ilia Foniakov held a meeting and poetic readings together with 
American poets from St. Petersburg (Florida, USA) on September 24th - October 16th.</p>
<p>The treaty about reconstruction of the Writers House between Turkish Construction firm 
and the City Council was concluded on October 6th, 1995. We hope that the restoration of 
the Writers House will be started soon. In October and November there were two 
representations of new books at the Writers Book Shop. Publications of &quot;Reminiscences&quot; of 
Academician Dmitrij Likhachev and the novel &quot;Escape to Russia&quot; of Daniil Granin became 
an outstanding event in cultural life of our city.</p>
<p>Michail Chulaki<br>
President of St.Petersburg Writers Union</p>
<p><a name="sweden"><font size=4><strong>News from</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> Sweden</strong></font></p>
<p>This autumn activities of the Swedish Writers Union (SWU) have been concentrated, 
mainly, on concluding a new basic agreement with the Swedish union of Publishers. Since 
our collecting society ALIS(cf. NEWSLETTER 95:2) was established, Swedish publishers 
have, very reluctantly, agreed to discussions on the rights of writers and translators. 
Publishers tend to see ALIS as a threat to their commercial interests. On the other hand, 
ALIS has come out to be the main defendant of the rights of writers and translators in the 
field of digital- electronic distribution. Discussions are, for the time being, very rancorous, 
but, still, there is a hope that publishers and authors might come to a common appreciation 
of this digital market.</p>
<p>Mr. Max Lundgren, newly elected chairman of the SWU and well-known author of books 
for young adults, has taken lead in bringing about solidarity actions for ALIS. So far, 900 
members of the SWU have signed agreements with this organisation, thus putting press on 
the publishers to recognise the aims of writers and translators to keep secondary rights for 
themselves.</p>
<p>International relations are developing along the lines set out during the Baltic Sea and the 
Black Sea Cruises. A meeting recently (Nov. 1995) in Kyjiv with Ukrainian writers proved 
to be most fruitful. Evidently, a number of Ukrainian writers will have the possibility of 
visiting the Gotland Centre in 1996. Also, the SWU took an active part in the joint 
Greek-Albanian Seminar (Nov. 1995, Visby) which, fortunately enough, resulted in a 
program for the establishment of a new centre on the Greek-Albanian-Macedonian border. 
Relations with the Czech Writers Union (Ms. Kanturkova) will be resumed during 1996: a 
seminar on Swedish Czech literary connections is being planned. Moreover, cooperation 
between the SWU and its counterpart in South Africa (COSAW) has entered a new phase. 
With the assistance of SIDA (Swedish International Development Agency) the SWU will 
share its experience of organisational and creative work with COSAW in order to build up 
a secure stand for South African authors. Finally, the SWU will ensure its presence in 
specific Nordic undertakings such as the Barent&#180;s project, where authors working North of 
the Polar circle can come together (Rovaniemi, Feb. 1996).</p>
<p>As for the view of the SWU, time now is ripe for the establishment of a NGO consisting of 
all European centres of writers and translators. Such a network will surely be influenced by 
the ideas developed by our Baltic centre.</p>
<p>Lars Erik Blomqvist<br>
2nd Vice President<br>
Swedish Union of Writers</p>
<p><a name="turkey"><font size=4><strong>To BWC writers</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> and translators organisations</strong></font></p>
<p>Dear friends,<br>
The Turkish PEN and the Turkish Writers Union is planning to organise a conference for 
literary translators who translate from Turkish into their won languages, in spring 1997 
(probably in April) in Istanbul. We would also like to publish a catalogue of all the books 
translated from Turkish. Please give us as soon as possible the names and addresses of the 
translators in your countries translating from Turkish. You can contact:<br>
Mrs Sezer Duru<br>
Turkish PEN<br>
General Yazgan sok. 10/10<br>
Mihti Apt.<br>
80050 Tunel - Istanbul<br>
Tel: +90-212-252 63 14<br>
Fax: +90-212-252 63 15<br>
Bets wishes to all of you<br>
Sezer Duru</p>
</body>

