<BODY>
<HR>
<H2><CENTER>Title: 12/19/95<BR>
Turkish Government Confiscates Magazine<BR>
</CENTER></H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=6>HUMAN RIGHTS WATCH PROTESTS <BR>
TURKISH GOVERNMENT'S CONFISCATION OF MAGAZINE<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
In a letter to Prime Minister Tansu Ciller of Turkey on December
19, 1995, the Human Rights Watch Arms Project protested against
the recent decision by a Turkish State Security Court to confiscate
all copies of the December 1995 issue of the magazine Savasa Karsi
Baris (Peace Against War). The issue contained a reprinted excerpt
of the Human Rights Watch Arms Project report Weapons Transfers
and Violations of the Laws of War in Turkey that was released
in Istanbul on November 21, 1995, and received wide coverage in
the Turkish media at the time.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Human Rights Watch is concerned that the Turkish government's
move to repress a journal for covering allegations of human rights
and humanitarian law violations that were already public appears
to be an attempt to set an example to other members of the media,
to stifle future criticism, and to warn independent writers to
exercise self-censorship on issues unfavorable to the government.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The confiscation constitutes a violation of Turkey's commitment
under Article 10 of the European Convention on Human Rights to
protect freedom of speech, and it comes on the heels of a vote
by the European Parliament to approve ratification of a customs
union treaty between Turkey and the European Union. While voting
in favor of ratification, the European Parliament also passed
a resolution, on December 13, 1995, urging the European Union,
its member states and Turkey to &quot;give their full backing
to a continuous and broad dialogue to promote respect for human
rights and freedoms,&quot; and calling on the Turkish Government
and the Grand National Assembly to &quot;continue the necessary
process of reform of the constitution and the criminal laws in
order to guarantee an ongoing improvement of the human rights
situation and democratic reform in Turkey.&quot;
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
A copy of the Human Rights Watch letter to Prime Minister Ciller
is attached.<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
December 19, 1995
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Prime Minister Tansu Ciller
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Basbakanlik
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Republic of Turkey<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Dear Prime Minister Ciller,
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Human Rights Watch Arms Project is a division of Human Rights
Watch, the largest international human rights organization based
in the United States. The Arms Project monitors and seeks to prevent
arms transfers and military aid to governments or organizations
that commit gross violations of internationally recognized human
rights and the rules of war. It also promotes freedom of expression
regarding arms transfers worldwide. It takes no position on political
or territorial issues in conflicts.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
I am writing to you regarding a December 12 court order, by Judge
Selahattin Cetin of the Fourth State Security Court, confiscating
the December issue (#12) of all copies of the monthly magazine
Savasa Karsi Baris. The order cited Article #28 of the Turkish
Constitution, as well as Penal Code #86, and Press Law #5680,
Appendix +, against this issue of the magazine because it reproduced
an excerpt of the most recent report produced by the Human Rights
Watch Arms Project, Weapons Transfers and Violations of the Laws
of War in Turkey. The excerpt, from our report's chapter on case
studies and titled &quot;Case 14,&quot; documents eyewitness accounts
of the destruction of the villages of Buzlutepe, Bilekli and surrounding
hamlets in Tunceli province carried out by Turkish security forces
using U.S. military equipment. It also documents other violations
of Common Article 3 of the Geneva Conventions, to which Turkey
is a signatory. Common Article 3 governs situations of internal
armed conflict. The case has been transferred to the State Prosecutor's
office, with the possibility that charges will be brought against
the owners.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Human Rights Watch strongly protests this action by the Turkish
government to deny the Savasa Karsi Baris and its editor Seyit
Soygan the right to free and non-violent expression of ideas.
Indeed, in this case, the magazine was merely reproducing the
results of research conducted by a separate organization, Human
Rights Watch, to which Savasa Karsi Baris has no connection. The
same information has already been released in Turkey in the completed
form of our report, and allegations similar to ours have been
made by Human Rights Watch/Helsinki, various foreign correspondents
and by the U.S. State Department's June 1995 Report on Allegations
of Human Rights Abuses by the Turkish Military and on the Situation
in Cyprus.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
In the view of Human Rights Watch, this court order, and any possible
charges that may follow, constitute a clear violation of Turkey's
commitments under Article 10 of the European Convention on Human
Rights to protect freedom of speech. This is a commitment which
Turkey ratified and incorporated into domestic law in 1954.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Last month, members of the Human Rights Watch Arms Project traveled
to Istanbul to publicly release this report: in a press conference
held on November 21, Turkish translations of excerpts of our report,
in addition to the completed English version, were distributed.
We are therefore concerned that the Turkish government's move
to repress a journal for covering allegations that were already
public appears to be an attempt to set an example to other members
of the media, to stifle future criticism, and to warn independent
writers to exercise self-censorship on issues unfavorable to the
government. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
We are moreover disturbed by the fact that the decision to confiscate
the December issue of the magazine was carried out soon after
the European Parliament voted to approve ratification of a customs
union treaty with Europe. It appears that the government of Turkey
is not sincere in its stated intent to reform legislation and
to end human rights violations in Turkey. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
We urge you to rescind the confiscation order on issue #12 of
the Savasa Karsi Baris and Mr. Seyit Soygan, to recommend that
the confiscated magazines be returned to the magazine's owners
forthwith, and to prevent any prosecution of the magazine and
its editors under the Penal Code. We also urge that the Turkish
government continue to make improvements to bring all elements
of Turkey's laws in accordance with internationally accepted standards
on human rights.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Sincerely,
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Joost R. Hiltermann<BR>
Director<BR>
Human Rights Watch Arms Project <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
cc: Ambassador Nuzhet Kandemir, Embassy of Turkey, Washington,
D.C.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Ambassador Marc Grossman,<BR>
United States Embassy, Ankara<BR>
Assistant Secretary of State John Shattuck, Washington, D.C.<BR>
Rep. Chris Smith, Helsinki Commission, United States Congress,
Washington, D.C.<BR>
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Human Rights Watch<BR>
485 Fifth Avenue<BR>
New York, NY 10017-6104<BR>
TEL: 212/972-8400<BR>
FAX: 212/972-0905<BR>
E-mail: hrwnyc@hrw.org<BR>
1522 K Street, N.W.<BR>
Washington D.C. 20005<BR>
TEL: 202/371-6592<BR>
FAX: 202/371-0124<BR>
E-mail: hrwdc@hrw.org <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
&copy; Human Rights Watch/Helsinki
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
</BODY>
