<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>C:\NETSCAPE\NEWS\TURK16.ASC</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>From: Human Rights Watch <BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=6>Title: HRW/Helsinki Calls on Clinton to
Raise Human Rights Issues During Meeting with Turkish President
Demirel <BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
In a letter today Human Rights Watch/Helsinki, the New York-based
rights organization, calls on President Clinton to make human
rights issues part of his agenda during an upcoming March 29,
1995, meeting with the President of the Republic of Turkey, Suleyman
Demirel. The letter, while acknowledging some improvements in
the human rights situation in Turkey in 1995, still notes severe
obstacles to respect for human rights in Turkey. Holly Cartner,
Executive Director of Human Rights Watch/Helsinki, stated that,
&quot;Turkey today stands at a crossroads. On the one hand Turkey
enjoys a largely free press that debates openly and critically
a wide range of issues, is home to a small but growing civil society,
and has hotlycontested local and national elections....On the
other hand, however, peaceful expression--including by the country's
most famous author, Yasar Kemal, and by duly-elected parliamentarians
of the banned Democracy Party--is sometimes punished under a variety
of laws, torture is widely used in pre-trial detention, and a
government counterinsurgency campaign against the PKK in the Kurdish-inhabited
southeastern region of the country has left over 2,000 villages
and hamlets depopulated and has violated the human rights of the
civilian population.&quot;<BR>
Human Rights Watch/Helsinki calls on President Clinton to raise
a number of issues with the Turkish Head of State to improve the
respect for fundamental rights in the country, including repealing
laws that punish free expression such as the 1991 Anti-Terror
Law and Articles 312, 159, 158, and 155 of the penal code, prosecuting
police alleged to have committed torture or abuse, amending the
Code of Criminal Procedure (CMUK) to reduce periods of pre-trial
detention, allowing greater cultural rights for Turkey's Kurdish
population, and appointing a State Minister Responsible for Human
Rights. Human Rights Watch/Helsinki expresses hope that the new
Yilmaz government would fulfill its promise to &quot;protect and
improve rights, freedoms, and the individual&quot; by instituting
some of the reforms cited above. &quot; The intimate relationship
between the United States and Turkey also means that the United
States has special responsibilities, including on human rights,&quot;
Cartner added. Human Rights Watch/Helsinki<BR>
Human Rights Watch is a nongovernmental organization established
in 1978 to monitor and promote the observance of internationally
recognized human rights in Africa, the Americas, Asia, the Middle
East and among the signatories of the Helsinki accords. It is
supported by contributions from private individuals and foundations
worldwide. It accepts no government funds, directly or indirectly.
Its Helsinki division was established in 1978 to monitor and promote
domestic and international compliance with the human rights provisions
of the 1975 Helsinki Accords. It is affiliated with the International
Helsinki Federation for Human Rights, which is based in Vienna,
Austria. <BR>
March 25, 1996<BR>
President William J. Clinton<BR>
The White House<BR>
1600 Pennsylvania Avenue<BR>
Washington, D.C.<BR>
[via fax] 456-2883<BR>
<BR>
Dear Mr. President:<BR>
We write to you today concerning your planned March 29th meeting
with Mr. Suleyman Demirel, President of the Republic of Turkey.
Human Rights Watch/Helsinki, a division of Human Rights Watch,
has been monitoring human rights in Turkey since 1983 and has
issued numerous reports on the situation there. We have also reported
on the situation of Turkish minorities in Bulgaria and Greece.
<BR>
Turkey today stands at a crossroads. On the one hand Turkey enjoys
a largely free press that debates openly and critically a wide
range of issues, is home to a small but growing civil society,
and has hotly-contested local and national elections. In 1995
there were some improvements in the human rights situation, and
certain Turkish government officials made positive statements
concerning human rights and took some steps to address human rights
problems. On the other hand, however, peaceful expression--including
by the country's most famous author, Yasar Kemal, and by duly-elected
parliamentarians of the banned Democracy Party--is sometimes punished
under a variety of laws, torture is widely used in pre-trial detention,
and a government counterinsurgency campaign against the PKK in
the Kurdish-inhabited southeastern region of the country has left
over 2,000 villages and hamlets depopulated and has violated the
human rights of the civilian population. Groups like Human Rights
Watch and Amnesty International, the United States Government
and the European Union, foreign journalists, and--most importantly-journalists,
political leaders, intellectuals, businessmen, and human rights
activists within Turkey, have all reported on and criticized these
abuses. Turkey must expand its democratic framework and remove
or amend laws and institutions that punish and hinder the development
of individual rights. <BR>
A little over two weeks ago, after much anticipation, the 53rd
government of the Republic of Turkey was founded under Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz. In the government's program, Prime Minister Yilmaz
promised to &quot;protect and improve rights, freedoms, and the
individual.&quot; In your upcoming meetings, we respectfully ask
you to raise the following points with President Demirel and encourage
him to work towards bringing about their realization:<BR>
<BR>
1. Free Expression<BR>
On October 27, 1995, the Turkish Grand National Assembly amended
Article 8 of the 1991 Anti-Terror law that punished so-called
&quot;separatist propaganda.&quot; As a result, at least one hundred
writers, intellectuals, and journalists were freed from prison.
Unfortunately, however, the amended version of Article 8 is still
being applied to punish peaceful expression. At least thirty five
individuals--including Yasar Kemal and several members of the
Human Rights Association of Turkey--have been sentenced or charged
under the amended Article 8 of the Anti-Terror Law or other of
its provisions. In addition, a host of other laws, such as Turkish
Penal Code [TPC] Article 312, inciting ethnic enmity, TPC Article
158, insulting the president, TPC Article 159, insulting the laws
of the republic, TPC Article 155, alienating people from military
service, and Law #5186, insulting the founder of the Turkish Republic,
are all used to punish free expression. Presently, several members
of the well-respected Human Rights Foundation of Turkey (HRFT)
stand trial under TPC Article 159 for a foundation publication.
We urge that these laws and all laws punishing peaceful, free
expression be abolished.<BR>
<BR>
2. Torture<BR>
Torture has been a recurring problem in Turkey, especially in
the ten southeastern provinces under emergency rule and in investigations
by the Anti-Terror Police Branch: Over the past three years at
least sixty-nine individuals have died as a result of torture
or maltreatment while in police custody: 1993, 29; 1994, 34; 1995,
6 (estimated). In 1995, the HRFT Torture Treatment Center reported
an increase in individuals seeking treatment because of police
abuse and torture. In January 1996, in a welcome statement, the
former Justice Minister, Firuz Cilingiroglu, announced that, &quot;In
Turkey, some insolent zealots, who are strangers to humanity,
resort to torture while fulfilling their security duties.&quot;
In the past, international and Turkish human rights organizations,
the Turkish press, as well as the European Committee to Prevent
Torture have documented cases of torture within the country. The
year 1995 witnessed more official statements condemning torture
and a somewhat more active attempt to prosecute abusive police,
both welcome moves. But as the recently-issued U.S. State Department
1995 Country Report noted, &quot; The climate of impunity that
the relatively small number of convictions [of police] created
probably remains the single largest obstacle to reducing...torture....&quot;
<BR>
We urge the Justice Ministry to play an active role in prosecuting
police who engage in torture and abuse and call on the new government
to work to amend the Code of Criminal Procedure (CMUK) that allows
for up to fifteen days of incommunicado detention, a number that
is doubled in the ten southeastern provinces under emergency rule.
The present Justice Minister, Mr. Mehmet Agar, who was the former
General Director of Security, should take strong actions against
torture and make the same public statements condemning torture
and police abuse as did his two most recent predecessors in the
Justice Ministry. We are concerned by a July 1995 statement Mr.
Agar made during the graduation ceremony at the Gaziantep Police
Academy, where he stated that, &quot;Today, there are some people
who deem human rights as terrorists rights and defend these rights
in our country. While my police officers and soldiers become martyrs,
they have no right to mention human rights.&quot; While the Turkish
police and security forces have a duty--indeed an obligation--to
fight crime and lawlessness, they have an equally strong obligation
to protect the rights of all citizens of Turkey, including those
suspected of committing crimes.<BR>
<BR>
3. Southeastern Turkey and the Kurdish Problem<BR>
For the past twelve years, the Turkish government has battled
the PKK, a militant Kurdish group that regularly violates human
rights in its actions. In addressing a legitimate security concern,
however, the Turkish security forces have habitually violated
the rights of those living in the region, mostly ethnic Kurdish
farmers and herders. Villagers in the region are in an untenable
position: if they join the government-sponsored village guard
system, they face violent retaliation from the PKK that is directed
at civilians and village guards alike, but if they refuse to join,
they face harassment, torture, and ultimately forced evacuation
by security forces. Consequently, at least 2,000 villages and
hamlets have been forcibly evacuated, most by government security
forces. A June 1995 State Department report indicated that U.S.-supplied
weapons had been used in some of these operations where the human
rights of civilians were violated. In addition, a wave of largely
unexplained death squad style killings (so called actor unknown
or mystery killings) and disappearances, totaling an estimated
1200, have swept over the region in the past four years. While
security forces over the past two years have arrested at least
seventy-five members of an armed Islamist extremist group, Hizbullah,
believed to have been responsible for at least seventy-one mystery
killings, the majority of the killings remain unsolved. Little
has been done to follow-up credible allegations pointing towards
some type of link between mystery killings and security forces.
The U.S. State Department 1995 Country Report cited a Turkish
parliamentary commission investigation into death squad killings
which concluded that &quot; illegal formations' within the state
bear some responsibility for mystery killings; they must be cleansed'...and
brought to justice.&quot; While the Turkish parliamentary commission's
report was a positive development, we urge the Turkish government
to follow-up on the commission's recommendations. <BR>
After its first cabinet meeting, a spokesman for the Yilmaz government
indicated that the state of emergency that has been in place over
most of southeastern Turkey since 1987 would shortly be lifted.
There was also talk of allowing private education in the Kurdish
language. While these are good initial steps, real initiatives
should be taken to address the legitimate rights of the Kurdish
population of the region and a state of emergency should not simply
replaced by other restrictive laws. Kurds in Turkey should be
able to enjoy Kurdish language newspapers, television and radio
programs, and education, whether private or public. While the
details of such initiatives are for the people of Turkey to work
out, some action in this direction must be taken.<BR>
<BR>
4. State Minister Responsible for Human Rights<BR>
In 1991, President Suleyman Demirel, then prime minister of a
newly-elected coalition government, instituted the office of State
Minister Responsible for Human Rights. The four men who have held
the post have made an important contribution in raising the public
debate about human rights in Turkey. In October 1994, Azimet Koyluoglu
condemned the government's abusive counterinsurgency campaign
in Tunceli province; in April 1995, Algan Hacaloglu condemned
a police raid in which three suspects were killed under suspicious
circumstances, calling it an &quot;extrajudicial killing.&quot;
In addition, Hacaloglu played an active role in a number of torture
cases so that police alleged to have committed abuses would be
brought to trial.<BR>
The present government of Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz has not
appointed anyone to the office of State Minister Responsible for
Human Rights. We urge the Yilmaz government, which has paid serious
attention to security concerns through the appointment of Mr.
Nahit Mentese, the former Interior Minister, as Deputy Prime Minister,
and through the appointment of Mr. Unal Erkan, the former Emergency
Rule Governor, as State Minister, to pay equal attention to human
rights and democratization through the appointment of a State
Minister Responsible for Human Rights. While it has been reported
that the government will increase the scope of the Parliamentary
human rights commission, we urge that the government do this as
well as appoint a State Minister Responsible for Human Rights.
<BR>
Turkey has been a U.S. ally for nearly fifty years and a member
of the Council of Europe since 1954. Last December, Turkey signed
a customs union agreement with the European Union, cementing an
association agreement signed in the early 1960s. While Turkey
has made some progress in human rights and democratization during
this period, there are still serious obstacles that prevent it
from fulfilling its international human rights obligations. We
respectfully urge you to raise the issues we have outlined with
President Demirel during your March 29th meeting. The intimate
relationship between the United States and Turkey also means that
the United States has special responsibilities, including on human
rights.<BR>
Respectfully,<BR>
Holly Cartner<BR>
Executive Director<BR>
Human Rights Watch/Helsinki<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
CC: Secretary of State Warren Christopher<BR>
Assistant Secretary of State John Shattuck<BR>
Ambassador Marc Grossman, U.S. Embassy, Ankara, Turkey<BR>
Human Rights Watch<BR>
485 Fifth Avenue<BR>
New York, NY 10017-6104<BR>
TEL: 212/972-8400<BR>
FAX: 212/972-0905<BR>
E-mail: hrwnyc@hrw.org<BR>
