<H2><CENTER>Approved: greta<BR>
Date: 7 June 96<BR>
From: hrwatchnyc<BR>
To: hrw-news<BR>
</CENTER></H2>
<H2><CENTER>Subject:<BR>
<FONT SIZE=6>Turkey Fails to Assist Forcibly Displaced in Southeast
<BR>
</FONT></CENTER></H2>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
10 June 1996 (Istanbul)--In Turkey's Failed Policy to Aid the
Forcibly Displaced in the Southeast released today, Human Rights
Watch/Helsinki charges that the Turkish government has violated
international and domestic law in its failure to provide adequate
assistance to the inhabitants of an estimated 2,685 villages and
hamlets fully or partially depopulated because of fighting in
southeastern Turkey. Since 1984, an armed conflict has raged in
Turkey's largely Kurdish-inhabited southeastern provinces between
government security forces and the PKK. While serious human rights
abuses characterize the behavior of both sides, most of the depopulation
is the result of a government counterinsurgency campaign intended
to deprive the PKK of logistic support. Human Rights Watch/Helsinki
executive director Holly Cartner states, &quot;The Geneva Conventions,
the European Convention for Human Rights, and Turkish domestic
law all set strict standards for either the forced movement of
the civilian population in a conflict or for its care and compensation
once a movement has been carried out. Turkey has failed on both
counts.&quot;<BR>
Even by the government's own estimates, at least 312,000 individuals
have been displaced, with other estimates running as high as two
million. Much of this displacement has occurred since 1992. In
spite of this crisis, government programs to care for the displaced,
such as the &quot;Central Villages Project&quot; or the &quot;Return
to the Village Project&quot;, were not announced until late 1994
and mid-1995 and then for various reasons never got off the ground.
Aid, such as food and tent disbursements, were ad hoc, when given
at all. In 1995, the United States State Department reported that
Turkish authorities had distributed U.S. $5.7 million to 32,260
forcibly displaced in southeastern Turkey. In 1994, the figure
was U.S. $772,000. The report, based largely on public press statements
by Turkish officials and ministers, depicts a disregard for the
plight of the displaced: in one October 1995 interview with the
Istanbul daily Cumhuriyet, then State Minister for Human Rights
Algan Hacaloglu, complained that, &quot;We evacuated villages
in the fight against terror, but after that we didn't fulfill
the requirements. People are living in tough conditions...&quot;
The report also criticizes the PKK for violations it has committed,
including attacks against village-guard civil militia settlements,
which has caused some families to flee their homes. <BR>
***<BR>
Copies of Turkey's Failed Policy to Aid the Forcibly Displaced
in the Southeast are available are available from the Publications
Department, Human Rights Watch, 485 Fifth Avenue, New York, NY
10017-6104, $3.60 (domestic), $4.50 (international). Visa/MasterCard
accepted.<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Human Rights Watch/Helsinki<BR>
</B>Human Rights Watch is a nongovernmental organization established
in 1978 to monitor and promote the observance of internationally
recognized human rights in Africa, the Americas, Asia, the Middle
East and among the signatories of the Helsinki accords. It is
supported by contributions from private individuals and foundations
worldwide. It accepts no government funds, directly or indirectly.
Kenneth Roth is the executive director and Robert L. Bernstein
is the chair of the board. Its Helsinki division was established
in 1978 to monitor and promote domestic and international compliance
with the human rights provisions of the 1975 Helsinki Accords.
It is affiliated with the International Helsinki Federation for
Human Rights, which is based in Vienna, Austria. Holly Cartner
is the executive director and Jonathan Fanton is the chair of
the advisory committee.<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
