<HR>
<H2><CENTER>Title: 7 June 96</CENTER></H2>
<H2><CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Peaceful Free Expression Punished During
UN Conference<BR>
</FONT></CENTER></H2>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Human Rights Watch is gravely concerned by reports that several
lawyers and administrators from the Istanbul Branch of the Human
Rights Association of Turkey (HRA) as well as families of prisoners
were detained today while trying to send a telegram to the Minister
of Justice dealing with prison conditions and reform. The incident
occurred at the main post office in Sirkeci, Istanbul, at 12:00
pm today. Among the detained include, Ercan Kanar, Zeynep Baran,
Suna Aras, and Ayhan Erkal, all members or administrators of the
Istanbul branch of the HRA and Mustafa Ucdere, head of the Istanbul
branch of the Contemporary Lawyers Association. Joanna Weschler,
Human Rights Watch U.N. representative, commented that, &quot;It
is unacceptable that at a time when Turkey is hosting a major
international conference like Habitat II the government interferes
with the free expression of its own citizens.&quot;<BR>
Human Rights Watch calls on the Turkish government to release
all these individuals and allow peaceful expression.<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER>***</CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Human Rights Watch/Helsinki <BR>
</B>Human Rights Watch/Helsinki was established in 1978 to monitor
and promote domestic and international compliance with the human
rights provisions of the 1975 Helsinki Accords. Jonathan Fanton
is the chair of the advisory committee and Alice Henkin is vice
chair. Holly A. Cartner is the executive director. Human Rights
Watch/Helsinki is a division of Human Rights Watch, which was
established in 1978 to monitor and promote the observance of internationally
recognized human rights worldwide. Kenneth Roth is the executive
director. Robert L. Bernstein is the chair of the board and Adrian
W. DeWind is vice chair.<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
