<HR>
<H2><CENTER>Title: 22 Aug 96</CENTER></H2>
<H2><CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Turkey: trial of author on the history
of human rights<BR>
</FONT></CENTER></H2>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
In a letter sent today to Prime Minister of Turkey Necmettin Erbakan,
Human Rights Watch/Helsinki condemned today's trial of the author
and the publisher of the book, Insan Haklar Tarihi (&quot;The
History of Human Rights&quot;). The New York-based monitoring
group protested charges filed under Article 8 of Turkey's Anti-Terror
Law against Mr. Erol Anar, vice secretary-general of the Human
Rights Association of Turkey, for a four-page chapter in the work
titled, &quot;Kurt Sorunu&quot; (&quot;The Kurdish Question&quot;).
The publisher of the book, zcan Sapan, also stands charged. They
are accused of &quot;separatist propaganda&quot; for focusing
in the short chapter on state relations with Turkey's Kurds in
both the Ottoman and Republican periods.<BR>
&quot;Mr. Anar's writings about Turkey's Kurdish minority, in
The History of Human Rights, fall clearly within the right to
peaceful self-expression,&quot; stated Holly Cartner, executive
director of Human Rights Watch/Helsinki. &quot;Turkey's Anti-Terror
Law is once again being used to punish unpopular, though peaceful
expression of dissent protected by international treaties Turkey
has signed,&quot; added Cartner. Article 8 of the 1991 Anti-Terror
Law has frequently been used to punish peaceful expression, especially
concerning the ethnic Kurdish population and the conflict in southeastern
Turkey between government security forces and the PKK. In late
1995, an amendment of Article 8 permitted the release from prison
of an estimate one hundred persons jailed for peaceful dissent;
however, many today are still being tried and punished under the
amended Article 8 and under other laws that stifle peaceful expression.
<BR>
A copy of the letter to Prime Minister Erbakan and an unofficial,
English-language translation of the book's controversial chapter,
&quot;The Kurdish Question,&quot; are attached. <BR>
Human Rights Watch/Helsinki<BR>
Human Rights Watch is a nongovernmental organization established
in 1978 to monitor and promote the observance of internationally
recognized human rights in Africa, the Americas, Asia, the Middle
East and among the signatories of the Helsinki accords. It is
supported by contributions from private individuals and foundations
worldwide. It accepts no government funds, directly or indirectly.
Kenneth Roth, executive director and Robert L. Bernstein is the
chair of the board. Its Helsinki division was established in 1978
to monitor and promote domestic and international compliance with
the human rights provisions of the 1975 Helsinki Accords. It is
affiliated with the International Helsinki Federation for Human
Rights, which is based in Vienna, Austria. Holly Cartner is the
executive director and Jonathan Fanton is the chair of the advisory
committee.<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
August 22, 1996<BR>
Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan<BR>
Republic of Turkey<BR>
Ankara<BR>
[By Fax]<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Dear Mr. Prime Minister:<BR>
Human Rights Watch/Helsinki is a division of Human Rights Watch,
the largest U.S.-based human rights organization in the world.
We have been monitoring human rights in Turkey since 1982 and
have issued numerous reports on a number of human rights topics.
I write to you today concerning today's August 22, 1996, trial
of Messrs. Erol Anar, Vice Secretary General of the Human Rights
Association of Turkey (Insan Haklari Dernegi) and author of Insan
Haklari Tarihi (The History of Human Rights) and &Ouml;zcan Sapan,
publisher at &Ccedil;iviyazilar Publishing house and publisher
of The History of Human Rights. Mr. Anar is being charged under
Article 8/1-3-4 of the 1991 Anti-Terror Law and Mr. Sapan under
Article 8/3-Press Law. The charges were reportedly filed because
of a four-page chapter, &quot;The Kurdish Question&quot;, (&quot;Kurt
Sorunu&quot;), in the 356-page book.<BR>
While one may argue intellectually or historically with the conclusions
Mr. Anar draws in the chapter, &quot;The Kurdish Question&quot;,
in his work, The History of Human Rights, it clearly falls within
the right of peaceful self-expression guaranteed under Article
10 of the<BR>
European Human Rights Convention, to which Turkey is a signatory.
I call on you to work towards repealing laws such as Article 8
of the Anti-Terror law that punish peaceful free expression and
limit debate in Turkey.<BR>
Respectfully,<BR>
Holly Cartner<BR>
Executive Director<BR>
Human Rights Watch/Helsinki<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
CC: Ambassador Nuzhet Kandemir, Turkish Embassy, Washington, D.C.
Asst. Secretary of State John Shattuck, Washington, D.C. Ambassador
Marc Grossman, U.S. Embassy, Ankara, Turkey<BR>
Hans Van den Broek, Member of the European Commission<BR>
Enclosure: &quot;Kurt Sorunu&quot;/&quot;The Kurdish Question&quot;
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
UNOFFICIAL ENGLISH TRANSLATION, &quot;The Kurdish Question&quot;
(&quot;Kurt Sorunu&quot;) in Anar, Author, 1996, Istanbul, Turkey.
<BR>
Published by &Ccedil;iviyazilar, Istanbul, Turkey<BR>
The Kurdish question is neither a question of economics as supporters
of the official ideology would have it, nor a question of terror.
Nor is the Kurdish question, a question of ethnic minorities.
In human rights literature, the Kurdish question falls within
the framework of `The Rights of Peoples`. The Kurds are a people
with a population of no less than 15 million deprived of the right
to life, right to fair trial and defense, the right to develop,
the right to peace, the right to environment, the right to freely
express its thoughts and the right to develop its own culture.
The Kurdish question is not a minority question, but rather a
question of a people's being able to express its identity freely.
<BR>
The Kurdish question did not begin with the establishment of the
Republic of Turkey. The Kurdish people were also repressed in
various ways during the Ottoman period but they also resisted.
Following the First World War, The Treaty of Sevres signed on
August 10, 1920, envisioned that `An independent Kurdistan would
be established in a certain section of the Eastern provinces`.
Moreover, the minorities would have the same political and judicial
rights as the Turks and would be proportionally represented in
the Assembly (Meclis). After February 17, 1920, the National Pact
(Misak-I Milli), which was declared `The Founding Principle of
the Turkish Nation`, proclaimed that `As soon as liberty is achieved
there will be a new free plebiscite in Kars, Ardahan and Batumi
which were annexed following a referendum` (Article 2). But with
the Lausanne Treaty of July 23, 1923, the boundaries of the National
Pact (Misak-I Milli) were recognized. Following this process,
the policies based on assimilation and denial of the Kurdish people
and minorities were continued even more.<BR>
Since the Ottoman era, the imperialist nations have pursued their
hypocritical policies on minorities and peoples living in Turkey.
On the one hand, they have tried to manipulate minorities and
peoples to further their own policies, on the other hand, they
have kept quiet in the face of massacres committed against these
minorities and peoples, and even supported such massacres. During
the Ottoman period these powers tried to manipulate the Armenians,
and later, during the first years following the establishment
of the Republic, the Kurds, but did not speak up against the massacres
committed against these people and have in fact supported them.
In spite of the fact that the British in particular tried to use
the Kurds towards their own ends, Kurdish rebellions and resistance
movements arose because of their own internal dynamics<BR>
The history of the Kurdish people from the Ottoman period onwards
to the Republic is interlaced with pain and resistance. During
the 19th century there were the revolts of the Revanduz, Bedirhan
Bey, Yezdan, Izzettin Ser and Sheik Beydullah. During the Republican
era, even more uprisings followed: Nasturi, Sheikh Sait, Rackotan,
Raman, Sason Netki, Koc Usagi, Asi Resul, Tenduruk, Savur, Zeylan,
Oromor and Dersim.<BR>
Starting with the Hozat Memorandum, the Kurdish struggle for equality
and freedom continued with the Xoybun (Independence) Congress,
composed of Turkish, Iraqi and Syrian Kurds. In several regions
the Xoybun representatives were able to establish control and
formed civil administrations. In June of 1930, as a result of
military operations by government forces, the independence movement
was defeated. Several leaders of Azadi, an illegal organization
that held its first congress in 1924, were arrested. Later, several
tribes gathered together around Sheikh Said and conquered Varto
and Elazig. The government declared martial law as a result of
the spread of the insurrection. During debates in the Grand National
Assembly, Ali Fuat Pasa, speaking as a representative of the Progressive
Republican Party, stated that: &quot;Insurrection movements, reactionary
movements should be suppressed. Let us make rebels and reactionaries
behave, and be brought into line. But let us not permit measures
that limit the natural rights or freedoms of citizens.&quot; As
for Ismet Inonu, he had stated that in order to prevent the repetition
of similar events, effective means would be taken. The meaning
of these effective means were to be understood later. Immediately
after the rebellion, the Law of Establishment of Public Order
and the establishment of two Independence courts was accepted
by a vote of 122 in favor and twentytwo against, and a real state
terror was unleashed against ethnic groups and minorities.<BR>
Between 1876 and 1935 in Dersim, where the state forces conducted
11 military operations, the repression continued without loosing
any of its initial momentum. With the Settlement Law, the people
of Dersim were subjected to forced migration. With the Tunceli
Law, emergency rule administration was established in Dersim.
During the Seyit Riza insurrection, airplanes of the Turkish Armed
Forces dropped bombs and poison gas over Dersim, and villages
and nomadic encampments were burned down. Then in 1927, a General
Inspectorate was established in the Kurdish- inhabited regions.
<BR>
In the Eastern Revolutionary Cultural Hearths (DDKO) trial many
individuals were tried and given various sentences.<BR>
Articles 26, 28 and 42 of the Constitution and the Law Concerning
Publications in Languages other than Turkish impedes the Kurds
from freely using their own language.<BR>
The Kurdish question--crucial question of democracy--is being
&quot;solved&quot; through military means. Through repressive
methods, the state attempts to suffocate the Kurds` rights to
express their own identity and their desire for a right to cultural
expression. In a message he sent to the Commander of the 15th
Regiment in Malatya, Ilyas Bey, dated Sept. 10 1919, Mustafa Kemal
said he wanted &quot;it to be announced everywhere that the Kurdish
movement would be eradicated at the root and that fleeing traitors
and those who agreed with them would be pitilessly exterminated.&quot;
Special warfare methods are being used against the Kurdish people,
and there are well over 300,000 soldiers and special team members
based in the region in addition to 61,000 village guards. According
to the announcements of the Chief of Staff, in figures for 1993,
military expenditures for the `low level conflict` prevailing
in the region amount to 150 trillion TL. According to a recent
research conducted by the presidency of the Chief of Staff, `Emergency
Region and Terror`, the hourly cost for the war amounts to 642
thousand dollars, or 28. 2 billion TL. In addition, a sum of 2.1
trillion TL is being paid a month to the soldiers serving in the
region.<BR>
The greatest numbers of applications made to Human Rights Commission
in the Grand National Assembly come from the region populated
by Kurds.<BR>
In the dirty war that has been going on for more than a decade,
thousands of individuals have fallen victim to `mystery killings`
and extrajudicial executions, 2,800 villages have been depopulated
by government forces, 3.5 million Kurds were forced to abandon
their homes and 20,000 people have lost their lives. Especially
since the 1990s the Kurdish question has been at the top of the
agenda and has functioned as a litmus test for intellectuals.
As we have mentioned earlier, the militarist-junta intellectual
type who is within the boundaries of the official ideology, has
unconditionally taken the side of official ideology. They have
stayed pure and have served these chauvinistic policies and the
continuation of the war. According to data from the Human Rights
Association, as of October 1995, 2546 villages have been depopulated.
Kurdish names of villages are also being changed. In addition
to a major prohibition from the Constitution, there are 13 different
laws that ban the expression of Kurdish language and culture.
<BR>
Today the Kurdish question has exceeded the boundaries of human
rights and acquired a political content. Since the 1990s it has
become clear that the Kurdish question, which has taken on new
dimensions and reached the international arena, cannot be solved
by military means, and that the only possible solution is a political
and democratic one. The solution lies in the ability of the Kurdish
people to put forward its demands freely, without any pressure.
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
