<html>
<head>
<title>Internet and literature - session 4</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><font size="7">Internet and Literature</font><br>
<font size="5">News from the seminar 23 september 1996</font></p>
<hr>
<h3>Copyright issues, creativity and freedom of expression</h3>
<p><b><img src="helge.JPG" align="left" hspace="10" width="200"
height="331"></b><b>Helge Sonneland</b>, from the Norwegian
Cultural Ministry, started the afternoon session by discussing
copyright-issues. </p>
<p>What is copyright? he asked. Copyright is an important
cultural legislation, but also a business legislation (3% of
Norways GNP comes for example from trades based on copyright). It
is, therefore, also in economic terms an important legislation.
The <i>raison d &ecirc;tre</i> of copyright is to stimulate
creativity in order to grant economic remuneration and hence
establish conditions for the creative work to continue. </p>
<p>Sonneland gave a short history of the copyright legislation:
From the first copyright statute in the world in Britain in 1709,
over the Berne convention from 1886 to the international
regulations of today. </p>
<p>In spite of the differences in national legislation &#147;we
are all, more or less, in the same boat&#148; said Sonneland who
presented the basic exclusive rights inherent in copyright. The
question is: What happens when the existing copyright legislation
confronts the Internet? A lot of problems occur. Which laws are
applicable? In the process of publishing on the net, <i>what</i>
copy is the one that should be covered by legislation - the one
on the server, on the readers hard drive, or the copy that is
printed out on paper etc? What kind of exemptions from the
exclusive right granted by law are needed in a digital age? What
is &#147;delivery on demand&#148; in copyright terms? </p>
<p>A lot of question that is in urgent need for solutions.
&#147;One thing is sure&#148;, Helge Sonneland concluded,
&#147;Copyright is not dead because of the Internet&#148;. </p>
<p><b><img src="gun.JPG" align="right" hspace="10" width="170"
height="258"></b><b>Gun Magnusson</b>, a lawyer representing
Copyswede, Sweden, has worked all her life with copyright issues.
She talked about copyright-problems in the digital era. But, as
she remarked, the questions are not new: &#147;Copyright has
always been a problem for the people who don't want to pay&#148;. </p>
<p>The copyright-agreements are quite different in different
parts of the world. For example in the Anglo-American world the
publishers or producers aquire much more rights than in Sweden,
where the writers keep a lot of their rights. But things are
changing, the media-situation is getting more complex, the fights
for rights more tough. But there is still a possibility to keep
the rights as a writer, Magnusson urged. Here both administrating
and technological methods are needed. They are at hand. Authors
are well organized. </p>
<p>Concerning administration Magnusson takes the publishing of an
homepage on Internet as an example. In this case it's the
legislation of the country where the homepage is published - that
is the country where the computer, the server, is situated -
which is relevant. </p>
<p>Concerning the technical methods, Magnusson points out that
the central question is about how to identify the authors, and
that means on an international basis. There are several attempts
made lately. 1994 an organization called <a
href="http://www.cisac.com">CISAC</a> was formed, and the
CIS-project started, which aims to create a code, CAE, for every
single author. There is also a project for creating another code,
ISWC, for the specific works, musical as well as literary and
visual. With multi-media, the situation is getting even harder;
but the most important thing is, as Magnusson repeated at the end
of her lecture: Hold on to your rights. </p>
<h5 align="center"><a href="01.htm">First session</a> | <a
href="02.htm">Second session</a> | <a href="03.htm">Thrird
session</a> | <a href="04.htm">Fourth session</a> | <a
href="05.htm">Fifth session</a></h5>
