<p><font size=2><strong>June 5, 1996</strong></font></p>
<h2><b>News from Visby</b></h2>
<p>The winter has been extremely long and quite cold even on Gotland, but in spite 
of all, and a rich inner life, we have survived and now see the light again. The 
Centre has been well utilized by visitors from East and West, and is now fully 
booked till November! Thanks to the scholarships granted by EU, the Local 
Government and others, plenty of well merited translators and writers have the 
possibility to come and use the Centre for a month as a working place with 
chances of having inspiring contacts with colleagues from other countries, And 
we have received lots of applications from all countries involved &#150; except for 
Denmark. There are still FIVE EU bursaries for SEK 6000 to be granted to 
FIVE Danish translators! Please spread this information and kindly ask all who 
are interested to contact the centre as soon as possible! The rooms are quickly 
getting booked for this year, Up to this moment we have only the most positive 
reactions and experiences from all our visitors. </p>
<p>The LIBRARY is in a process of building up. Our librarian <strong>Janet Wamby</strong> has 
done a good job, but there is still lots of work to do. It goes slowly but surely 
and we still need to repeat our urgent request to all of you that we need books &#150; 
mainly dictionaries and reference literature, but also other interesting works. </p>
<p><strong>Anette Glover</strong> is leaving the Centre and moving with her family to Stockholm, 
which we deeply regret. This means that we have to find someone to replace her 
pretty soon. For the summer vacations <strong>Sasja Afinigenova</strong>, translator of 
Swedish from Moscow, will be in charge of the daily duties at the Centre. 
Gunilla has her summer holidays in July. </p>
<p>We are sorry to inform about the negative answer to our application to EU, 
signed by all the member associations in October 95, concerning the project to 
create an Internet network between our countries. This means that at the 
moment we will have to put it on the ice, but maybe we can take it up again and 
work it out better in the future! </p>
<h3 align=center><b>The Centre of Visby and Rhodos a part of the UN's cultural 
program</b> </h3>
<p>The most positive news right now is a letter from <strong>Federico Mayor</strong> to <strong>Peter 
Curman</strong>, confirming that UNESCO &#147;in view of the importance of the centres 
created by your organization for a peace&#150;building process which UNESCO is 
seeking to promote by every possible means, I agree that the Baltic Centre for 
Writers and Translators (Gotland) may operate under UNESCO's 
auspices.&#147;<br>
The same goes for our sister centre on Rhodos, which will be inaugurated on 
September 22. This strengthens our status as an international centre and 
authorizes us to use the emblem of UNESCO, Most of all it opens up new 
possibilities for financial assistance from UNESCO for the organizations of 
international seminars and meetings within the centres. We are very grateful for 
this and want to express our thanks to Peter Curman for his achievements. </p>
<p><b>The Board</b> of the Centre has had two meetings this year, on January 19th and 
May 24th. The members of the board are now <strong>Thorsten Andersson</strong> 
(Governor of Gotland), chairman, <strong>Peter Curman</strong> and <strong>Lars Erik Blomqvist</strong> 
(Swedish Writers' Union), <strong>Sonia Landin</strong> (Municipality of Gotland), <strong>Lars 
Magnus Lahne</strong> (College for Higher Studies on Gotland), <strong>Jarkko Laine</strong> 
(Finland) and <strong>Alexander Branski</strong> (Russia) &#150; the two latest members elected by 
vote on the last BWC meeting, one of them representing all the former Western 
countries and one the former east. The next meeting will be held on <em>October 
25th</em> in Gothenburg in connection with the Book Fair. </p>
<p>During the spring we had two big projects, one of them a series of six lectures 
about modern Baltic literature in collaboration with the Library and 
Folkuniversitetet. These lectures reached a great public and gave many 
interesting aspects and literary temperaments, from Lars Erik Blomqvist's expos&eacute; 
of modern prose and development in Russia to the great Finnish&#150;Swedish 
modernist Gunnar Bj&ouml;rling and three Latvian poets: Knuts Skujenieks, Juris 
Kronbergs and Ludmila Azarova.<br>
The second big spring event was a Conference on May 3-4 in Visby &#150; at the 
same time as the Baltic Prime Ministers' Meeting &#150; on Freedom of Expression, 
information and libraries.<br>
The Centre was involved mainly in the first days' panel dedicated to the 
Freedom of expression, with Jaan Kaplinski, Knuts Skujenieks, Jean Guiloineau, 
Peter Curman, Antanas Jonynas and Arne Ruth as moderator. Andrei Bitov and 
Adam Michnik had also promised to participate, but both jumped off just before 
the conference, which we do regret. To this conference came altogether some 
70 participants from all the Baltic region. It gave many contacts and ideas for the 
future and ended with an unforgettable medieval dinner. </p>
<h3 align=center>Coming activities </h3>
<p>In this very moment we are planning the detailed program for THE THIRD 
INTERNATIONAL POETRY FESTIVAL on GOTLAND <em>13-16 of June</em>.<br>
The Centre is organizing it all and has succeeded in finding the sponsors and 
some thirty persons to invite. There will be four days and nights with readings 
and singing and music all over the island, from F&aring;ro to the south of Gotland.<br>
We are expecting <strong>Agneta Pleijel</strong>, <strong>Gabriela Melinescu</strong>, <strong>Marie Lundquist</strong>, 
<strong>LiLi</strong>, <strong>Peter Curman</strong>, <strong>Juris Kronbergs</strong>, <strong>Kjell Espmark</strong>, <strong>Ulla Roseen</strong>, 
<strong>Anders Bodeg&aring;rd</strong>, <strong>Magnus Nilsson</strong>, <strong>Per W&auml;stberg</strong>, <strong>Steinunn 
Sugurdardottir</strong>, <strong>Bo Carpelan</strong>, <strong>Jarkko Laine</strong>, <strong>Doris Kareva</strong>, <strong>Guntars 
Godi&ntilde;&szlig;</strong>, <strong>Sigitas Geda</strong>, <strong>Nijol&eacute; Miliauskaite</strong>, <strong>Bronislaw Maj</strong>, <strong>Blaga 
Dimitrova</strong>, <strong>Ileana Malancioiu</strong>, <strong>Victor Krivulin</strong> and many others. </p>
<p>&#147;WRITING FOR CINEMA&#147; we call a small but very interesting seminar in the 
<em>first week of September</em>, organized by the Centre together with <strong>Elisabeth 
Edlund</strong>, film expert at the County Administration and sponsored by the Swedish 
Institute. We want to invite some 12-15 persons from all the region, persons 
with a burning passion for this media and with different kind of experience. Have 
you got ideas? <br>
The seminar will end by joining the annual Baltic Film festival in Bursvik on the 
south of Gotland. </p>
<p>&#147;LA PRESENCE BALTE&#147; takes place in Paris, <em>October16-20</em> and is a 
collaboration with Centre Culturel Suedois,UNESCO, Ars Baltica and the 
Swedish Institute. The Centre is responsible for the literary part of the project, 
which will be the heart of it all. The idea is to present cultural aspects of Estonia, 
Latvia in Lithuania with some smaller parts from other countries too on Swedish 
ground in Paris, the beautiful palace in the Marais quarter. Well known writers 
like <strong>Jaan Kross</strong>, <strong>Tonu Onnepalu</strong> (<strong>Emil Tode</strong>) from Estonia, <strong>Vizma 
Belsevica</strong> and <strong>Knuts Skujenieks</strong> from Latvia are taking part. From Sweden 
are coming <strong>Magnus Florin</strong> and <strong>Marie Lundquist</strong>. In this moment the 
Lithuanian part is settled yet, but the idea has been to build it up around 
Ciurlionis. Lithuanian ambassador Mrs, <strong>Ugn&eacute; Karvelis</strong> is involved in the 
project. </p>
<p>Well, this is a short summary of the most important happening and events. We 
are now very much looking forward to the big event on Rhodos, the 
<a href="http://www.marebalticum.se/rhodes/programme-96sept.htm">INAUGURATION of our sister Centre</a> on the 26nd of September. Hope to 
meet many of you there! Till then I wish you all a long and warm and creative 
summer! </p>
<p><em>Gunilla Fors&eacute;n</em> </p>
<p>Director </p>
<hr>
<h2><b><i>Quo vadis </i></b><b>Baltic Writers' Council?</b> </h2>
<p>On <em>May 25</em> we had also a reduced Board meeting of the Baltic Writers' 
Council, regretfully <strong>Uwe Friesel</strong>, <strong>Jarkko Laine</strong> and <strong>Alexander Branski</strong> 
could not come to Visby, so <strong>Inguna Bekere</strong> and representative from 
St.Petersburg Writers' union <strong>Julia Fedjakova</strong> had a joint meeting with 
representatives form the Centre's administrative Board - <strong>Peter Curman</strong>, <strong>Lars 
Erik Blomqvist</strong>, director of the centre <strong>Gunilla Forsen</strong> and International 
Secretary of Gotlandic Municipality <strong>Robert Hall</strong>. </p>
<p>The main issue discussed was related to the October meeting of the Baltic 
Writers Council, that is &#150; <i>Quo vadis BWC?</i> </p>
<p>Following from the meeting in October,the Minutes of which were one of the 
Appendices of the previous Newsletter, we have to find clear answers to several 
questions: Should there be new bylaws, new principles of election, membership 
fee, registered association. Even though the discussions focused mainly on formal 
issues &#150; the legal setup, election principles of the board, etc., it seems that more 
important would be to start discussion about the way Baltic Writers' Council 
should function in the future, especially its involvement in the activities in the 
Centre. The leitmotif of the October meting was &#150; &#147;the honeymoon is over&#147; 
(P.Curman). And, of course, honeymoons are made to come to an end to to run 
into a different kind of relationship.. </p>
<p>The two elected speakers of BWC &#150; Uwe Friesel and me, Inguna Bekere, met 
in Stockholm in February and discussed various legal possibilities and prospects 
for development. It seems that mere changes in the legal status of BWC would 
not be sufficient to make its members more involved in the activities of the 
organization and the Centre, There is also a feeling that BWC has been a 
democratic and friendly organization (even though not an officially registered 
one) and it should not be too bureaucratized. </p>
<p>As a result of this meeting a questionnaire was sent out to all BWC member 
organizations, in which the member organizations were asked to think about the 
problems and possible development of the organization and to send their 
answers to the following questions: </p>
<p>Should BWC remain a network of organizations or be restructured into a formal, 
registered association? Any other possible forms of existence? Have you any 
concrete suggestions for the statutes of the BWC, the election process and 
principles? Irrespective of its formal set-up, what should be the main objectives 
and priorities of the BWC in view of the changed political, economic and cultural 
situation in Europe, also in the Baltic region? What news channels for the 
exchange of information? How can we facilitate our access to internet and 
e-mail? What kind of projects BWC wants and can carry out? What should the 
budget of the BWC be? Should there be a membership fee and amount of it? 
Could the so called Eastern countries finance their own travel cost for the future 
BWC meetings in the future? What should be the official address of the BWC? 
How should BWC interact with the Baltic Centre of Writers and Translators? </p>
<p>We had very few responses, and only one of them in written form &#150; from our 
Finnish colleagues, which follows below: </p>
<p><strong>1.</strong> We consider that BWC is a well-functioning <em>network</em> between the 
organizations of writers and translators in the countries around the Baltic Sea. 
We also think that BWC should remain as it is, and should not become a 
registered association or something of that type. We already have NFR, EWC. 
FIT and CEATL, and there is no need for overlapping. </p>
<p><strong>2.</strong> The revision of the statutes should <em>start from the existing statutes</em>. A 
proposal for changes should be made by a small group &#150; such as the present 
Board &#150; and it should then be sent out for comments. </p>
<p><strong>3.</strong> BWC should discuss questions <em>that are taken up by the member 
organizations and that concern writers and translators</em>. </p>
<p>We consider that BWC should have a meeting once a year &#150; preferably as until 
now &#150; in October. Every year in August, all member organizations can submit 
proposals on issues that they would like to take up at the meeting. The proposals 
are combined by the Centre in Visby to make and agenda, which is then sent in 
September to the member organizations. </p>
<p>BWC needs no Board. </p>
<p>Within BWC, joint issues can be <em>discussed</em>, members can be <em>informed</em> about 
questions of mutual interest, and <em>opinions can be expressed</em>. </p>
<p><strong>4.</strong> Exchange of information must naturally take place using means that are 
available &#150; by post, telephone, fax or e-mail, depending on what the recipient 
can receive. </p>
<p><strong>5.</strong> BWC `s projects should <em>concern writers and/or translator</em> in the various 
countries. All member organizations can submit proposals for projects. </p>
<p><strong>6.</strong> As a rule, BWC's budget should be <em>based on projects</em>. Projects should 
cover their own costs. </p>
<p><strong>7.</strong> We <em>do not</em> think that BWC should collect a membership fee. After all, the 
sum could not be as High as to be of crucial importance for activities. </p>
<p><strong>8.</strong> Our opinion is that all member organizations should pay for their delegates' 
travel costs, board and lodging themselves. To the extent possible, the Centre 
should offer accommodation free of charge for delegates who need it. </p>
<p><strong>9.</strong> BWC's official address should be the Centre in Visby. </p>
<p><strong>10.</strong> The Centre's director serves as the coordinator between the Centre and the 
Council. The newsletter is compiled in the Centre. The Centre convenes the 
General Meeting, sends out the agenda and arranges the premises for the 
meeting. </p>
<p><strong>11.</strong> We consider that the Centre's director should also be hear in all of the above 
questions. </p>
<p>Union of Finnish Writers </p>
<p><em>Jarkko Laine <br>
</em>Chairman </p>
<p>Society of Swedish Writers in Finland </p>
<p><em>Agneta Ara <br>
</em>Chairwoman </p>
<p>Finnish association of Translators and Interpreters </p>
<p><em>Kristiina Rikman</em> <br>
Chairwoman </p>
<hr>
<p>We heard also the opinions of Swedish Writers' Union's representatives, 
Latvian, Estonian and St.Petersburg views. </p>
<p>It seems that there are now two directions of thought. </p>
<p>The first one, which also is more related to the discussions of the October 
meeting of BWC, is to remake BWC into official registered organization, have a 
membership fee, elected board and chairperson, and make the organization 
stronger and more independent. </p>
<p>The other view is to keep the informal character of BWC, use it as a network, 
centered very much round the centre in Visby, as the very existence of the BWC 
has organically grown from the Centre in Visby. </p>
<p>During the meeting in Visby now in May no definite conclusion was reached, as 
the opinions of all member organizations were not made known to us. </p>
<p>It seems, though, that the next meeting of the BWC in Visby could be organized 
in <em>February, 1997</em>, as October is quite a busy period for many of us. It will also 
give us time to have a discussion on all the problems related to the future of 
BWC. </p>
<p>We still expect all our member organizations to come back in writing and 
express their views about the future of BWC, giving their reasons for either of 
the options &#150; registered organization or a network. These could be circulated in 
autumn in our Newsletter, which could turn into a forum for discussion and bring 
us closer to a definitive conclusion. </p>
<p><em>Inguna Bekere</em> <br>
1/2 Speaker, BWC </p>
<hr>
<h2>News from Writer Organizations</h2>
<h4>Changes and reelections: </h4>
<p><strong>Helkky Halme</strong>, Office manager of the <em>Finnish Association for Translators 
and Interpreters</em> informed us that the section for literary translators has a new 
chairwoman, <strong>Anna&#150;Maija Viitanene</strong>. She has been elected for two years &#150; 
1996-1997. </p>
<p><strong>Witold Skowronski</strong> informs us that in the <em>Association of Polish Translators 
and Interpreters</em> the following changes have taken place as a result of elections 
to the Main Board, the following persons have been elected for the term 
1996-1999: </p>
<p>President: Mr.<strong>Witol Skowronski </strong><br>
V.-President: Mr.<strong>Krzystof Brezinski</strong> <br>
V.-President: Mr.<strong>Wojciech Gilewski</strong> <br>
Secretary: Mrs.<strong>H.Krochmalewska</strong> <br>
Treasurer: Mrs <strong>I.Sikora-Chmielewska</strong> <br>
Member: Mr. <strong>Marek Cegiela</strong> <br>
Member: Mr. <strong>Tomasz Zebrovski.</strong> </p>
<p>Some changes have occurred also in the <em>Writers' Union of St.Petersburg</em>. 
<strong>Alexander Branski</strong> is now working at the City Municipality, <strong>Julia Fedjakova</strong> 
is now working as the International Secretary of the Union. </p>
<p>We wish lots of success in their work to all the newly elected persons! </p>
<hr>
<h3>Some Literary Events in Tallinn</h3>
<p>After a period of transitional confusion an attempt was made to clear the position 
and role of literature under the new social conditions, commonly called &#147;market 
economy&#147;. Organized by the Writers' Union of Estonia, a literary conference 
called &#147;The Writer on the market&#147;, took place in Tallinn in <em>May 15-16</em>, 12 
writers and critics had the opportunity to express their views on the theme. A 
wide-ranged spectre of opinions tackled almost all important issues, which 
connect the two terms &#147;literature&#147; and &#147;market&#147;. The general attitude towards 
the huge complex was positively analytical and prompted in essayistic manner. 
The look back into the past was best put into words perhaps by <strong>Jaan 
Kaplinski</strong>, who compared the change with moving out from the socialist harem 
into the capitalist brothel. <strong>Jaan Kross</strong> and <strong>Teet Kallas</strong> spoke about the 
metamorphoses in the market and ourselves in a more personal way. <strong>Cornelius 
Hasselblatt</strong> from Hamburg described the reception of Estonian authors on 
German market, suggesting some ideas how we, Estonians could help in 
promoting our literature. <strong>Piret Viires</strong> gave an informational survey about 
publishing in Estonia and &#147;making of an author&#147;. <strong>Tonu Onnepalu</strong> stated that an 
author must think on writing, leaving the selling business to other authorities. 
<strong>Mart Valjataga</strong>, <strong>Marju Lauristin</strong> and <strong>Hasso Krull</strong> developed more 
theoretical&#150;philosophical ideas. <strong>Rein Veidemann</strong> spoke about the critics on the 
market and <strong>Toomas Liiv</strong> about entertainment in market-connections. There is a 
plan and money to publish all the materials in book-form during in autumn. </p>
<p>On the first evening there was a poetry-reading on the street: in the Old Markets 
Neck. Some ten poets presented their texts despite grim weather. It happens 
seldom that temperature sinks more than 20 degrees in one night. It was 5-6 
degrees Celsius on May 15! The literary beer &#147;Czar's madman&#147;, sponsored by 
the Saku Brewery, was tasted and cheered before and afterwards, on street it 
was just too cold. </p>
<p>The conference was followed by the seminar for the international translators of 
Estonian literature in the Palmse manor not far from Tallinn. The last one had 
taken place in 1991, so there was a real need to inform our guests, altogether 
30, from many European countries, about changes in Estonia and its literature. 
The delivered lectures fulfilled this purpose. </p>
<p>The last thing to mention: all this was financed by Estonian Culture capital. 
Estonian Ministry of Culture and Open Estonian Foundation (Soros). Thanks to 
all of them! </p>
<p><em>Mati Sirkel <br>
</em>President, <br>
Estonian Writers' Union </p>
<hr>
<h3>A Short Report from the Writers' Union of St.Petersburg </h3>
<p>December, 1995. The annual ceremony of awarding the <strong>Beljaev's Prize</strong> took 
place at Pushkin's Museum on Moika embankment. The final winners are as 
follows: <strong>Svjatoslav Loginov</strong> and <strong>Vjacheslav Rybakov</strong> in the nomination of 
SF literature, <strong>Igor Vjortkin</strong> (Great Britain), <strong>Genrich Altshuller</strong> and <strong>Sergej 
Rjazantsev</strong> for popular science literature. <strong>Tatiana Usova</strong> for the best 
translation of SF literature into Russian and &#147;<strong>Polygon</strong>&#147; Publishing House for the 
best publishing s eries. </p>
<p>February, 1996. Six Swedish writers: <strong>Sven&#150;Arne Andersson</strong>, <strong>Annika 
B&auml;ckstr&ouml;m</strong>, <strong>Lars B&auml;ckstr&ouml;m</strong>, <strong>Peter Curman</strong>, <strong>Mvandaviro Mganga</strong> and 
<strong>Siv Widerberg</strong> visited St. Petersburg writers, translators, philologists, critics, 
librarians, journalists from leading city's newspapers and radio stations, 
representatives of Swedish Consulate General in St.Petersburg. </p>
<p>March, 1996. St.Petersburg Writers' Union held several memorial events 
dedicated to <strong>Joseph Brodsky</strong>, whose sudden death shocked his friends, 
colleagues and admirers. </p>
<p>One of the most interesting literary events in April became the presentation of 
new book by St.Petersburg literary critic <strong>Irma Kudrova</strong> &#147;<em>Ruin of Mariza 
Zvetajeva</em>&#147;, which covers the last period in the life of <strong>Marina Zvetajeva</strong> in the 
USSR till her tragic death in Elabuga. This work by Irma Kudrova contains a lot 
of documents from KGB archives, which were formerly closed for research. </p>
<p>On the 16th of May there was a general meeting of St.Petersburg Writer's 
Union, dedicated to problems of modern Russian literature. International Book 
fair &#147;St.Petersburg Book Salone&#147; will be opened at the great exhibition hall 
&#147;Manege&#147; on 24-27th of May, 1996. St.Petersburg Russian PEN Club will 
present at this Book fair the 1st issue of its new literary magazine &#147;Mansarda&#147;. </p>
<p><em>Julia Fedjakova</em> <br>
International Secretary<br>
Writers' Union of St.Petersburg </p>
